Distributed web infrastructure
==============================

A user wants to access the website www.foobar.com from a browser.

1. The user types https://www.foobar.com in the browser.
2. The browser asks DNS to translate www.foobar.com into an IP address.
3. The DNS zone for foobar.com has a www record that points to the public IP
   address of the HAproxy load balancer.
4. The browser connects to the load balancer using HTTP or HTTPS over TCP/IP.
5. HAproxy receives the request and forwards it to one of the two backend
   servers.
6. The selected server's Nginx web server receives the request.
7. Nginx serves static content directly or forwards dynamic requests to the
   application server on the same machine.
8. The application server runs the application code from its local application
   files.
9. If data is needed, the application server communicates with MySQL.
10. Write operations go to the Primary MySQL node.
11. Read operations can go to a Replica MySQL node if the application is
    configured to use replicas for reads.
12. The response is sent back through Nginx, then HAproxy, then to the user's
    browser.

Infrastructure
--------------

Load balancer:

    HAproxy
    Public entry point for www.foobar.com

Server 1:

    Components:
        - Nginx web server
        - Application server
        - Application files, which are the website code base
        - MySQL Primary database

Server 2:

    Components:
        - Nginx web server
        - Application server
        - Application files, which are the website code base
        - MySQL Replica database

Why each additional element is added
------------------------------------

The HAproxy load balancer is added to distribute incoming traffic between the
two backend servers. This helps the infrastructure handle more traffic than a
single server and allows one backend server to continue serving requests if the
other backend server becomes unavailable.

The second server is added to increase capacity and improve availability. Each
server has its own Nginx web server, application server, application files, and
MySQL database instance, so the application can run from more than one machine.

The second Nginx web server is added so both backend servers can receive and
handle HTTP requests from the load balancer.

The second application server is added so dynamic application logic can be
executed on both backend servers.

The second set of application files is added so both backend servers have the
same code base and can serve the same website.

The second MySQL database is added to create a Primary-Replica database setup.
This improves database availability and can improve read performance if the
application sends read queries to the Replica.

Load balancing algorithm
------------------------

HAproxy is configured with the Round Robin distribution algorithm.

Round Robin sends requests to backend servers one after another in order. For
example, the first request goes to Server 1, the second request goes to Server
2, the third request goes back to Server 1, and so on.

This algorithm is simple and works well when the backend servers have similar
hardware and are expected to handle similar amounts of traffic.

Active-Active or Active-Passive
-------------------------------

This load balancer configuration enables an Active-Active setup for the backend
web servers.

In an Active-Active setup, all backend servers are online and receive traffic at
the same time. In this infrastructure, both Server 1 and Server 2 can serve user
requests through HAproxy.

In an Active-Passive setup, one server actively receives traffic while another
server waits as a standby. The passive server only starts receiving traffic if
the active server fails.

Database Primary-Replica cluster
--------------------------------

In a MySQL Primary-Replica cluster, the Primary database receives write
operations such as INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE. The Primary records these changes
in its binary logs.

The Replica database copies the changes from the Primary and applies them to
keep its data synchronized. Replication is usually asynchronous, which means the
Replica can be slightly behind the Primary for a short time.

Difference between Primary and Replica for the application
---------------------------------------------------------

The Primary node is the database node used by the application for write
operations. It is the source of truth for new or changed data.

The Replica node is mainly used for read operations. The application can query
the Replica for data that does not need to be immediately up to date. The
application should not send normal write operations to the Replica, because the
Replica is meant to copy data from the Primary.

Issues with this infrastructure
-------------------------------

SPOF:

    The HAproxy load balancer is a single point of failure. If it goes down,
    users cannot reach the backend servers even if both backend servers are
    healthy.

    The MySQL Primary database is also a single point of failure for writes. If
    the Primary goes down, the application cannot safely write new data unless a
    Replica is promoted to become the new Primary.

    If the DNS record points to only one load balancer IP address, that entry
    point can also contribute to the single point of failure.

Security issues:

    There is no firewall, so services may be exposed to networks that should not
    be able to access them. For example, the database should not be reachable
    directly from the public internet.

    There is no HTTPS termination described, so user traffic may be sent without
    encryption if plain HTTP is used. This can expose passwords, cookies, and
    other sensitive data.

No monitoring:

    There is no monitoring system to track server health, application errors,
    traffic, CPU usage, memory usage, disk usage, database replication delay, or
    service availability. Without monitoring, failures may not be detected
    quickly.
